<paragraphs xml:id="notation-for-pure-time-des">
<title>Notation for pure-time DEs</title>

<p> In general, we study a pure-time differential
equation <m>\displaystyle \frac{dF}{dt} = f(t)</m>.
</p>

<p> Solving this pure-time DE for the unknown
function <m>F(t)</m> involves finding the function whose derivative is
<m>f(t)</m>. We want to <sq>undo</sq> the derivative to find
<m>F(t)</m>, called the <em>antiderivative</em> of <m>f(t)</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-antiderivative">
<title>antiderivative</title>
<statement> <p>An <term>antiderivative</term> of the function
<m>f(t)</m> is a function <m>F(t)</m> whose derivative equal to
<m>f(t)</m>. We say, <q><m>F</m> of <m>t</m> is equal to the integral of
<m>f</m> of <m>t</m> with respect to <m>t</m>,</q> and we write <me>F(t)
= \int f(t)\,dt.</me>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="warning">
<title>Warning</title>

<p> The equation <m>\displaystyle\frac{dp}{dt} =
1.8</m> has solution <me>p(t) = \int 1.8\,dt = 1.8t+c.</me> What is
<m>c</m>?
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-indefinite-integral">
<title>indefinite integral</title>
<statement>
<p> The set of all antiderivatives of the function
<m>f(t)</m> is called the <term>indefinite integral</term> of <m>f</m>
and
is written <me>\int f(t)\,dt = F(t) + c.</me></p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p> Solve pure-time DE <me>\frac{dF}{dt} = 2</me> by
computing the indefinite integral.
</p>

<p> Solve pure-time DE <me>\frac{dF}{dt} = 2t</me>
by computing the indefinite integral.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-power-integral">
<statement>
<p>Suppose that <m>f(x) = x^n</m> with
<m>n\neq-1</m>, then <me>\boxed{\int
x^n\,dx=\left(\frac{1}{n+1}\right)x^{n+1}+c}</me>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="ex-indef-basic">
<statement><p>Compute <m>\displaystyle \int x^{2}\,dx</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-antideriv-basic">
<statement><p> Compute the indefinite integral of
<m>\displaystyle g(x)=x^{0.4}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-indef-basic2">
<statement><p> 
Compute <m>\displaystyle \int t^5\,dt</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-antideriv-basic2">
<statement>
<p> Compute the indefinite integral of
<m>\displaystyle f(t)=\frac{1}{t^{4}}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="thm-constant-product-integral">
<title>Constant product rule for integrals</title>
<statement>
<p>Suppose that <m>\displaystyle \int
f(x)\,dx=F(x)+c</m>, then for any constant <m>a</m>, <me>\boxed{\int
af(x)\,dx=a\int f(x)\,dx= aF(x)+c}</me>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \int 12t^5\,dt</m>.
</p>

<p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \int
\frac{3}{t^{4}}\,dt</m>.
</p>

<p> Suppose that <m>\displaystyle \int
f(x)\,dx=F(x)+c</m> and <m>\displaystyle \int g(x)\,dx=G(x)+c</m>, then
<me>\boxed{\int f(x)+g(x)\,dx=\int f(x)\,dx +\int g(x)\,dx=
F(x)+G(x)+c}</me>
</p>

<p> Compute <m>\displaystyle \int 12t^5 +
\frac{3}{t^{4}}\,dt</m>.
</p>

<p> Consider a seed in a flower in a very tall tree.
From an initial height of 14.7 meters, the seed pops straight into the
air with an initial velocity of 9.8 meters per second (<m>\displaystyle
v(0)=9.8~\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}}</m>) and an acceleration due to
gravity of <m>\displaystyle
a(t)=-9.8~\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s${}^{2}$}}</m> (in the downward
direction). Find the velocity function <m>v(t)</m> and use that to find
its position function <m>s(t)</m> of the seed.
</p>

<p><ol>
<li> <p> When will the seed land?</p> </li>
<li> <p> What is the velocity of the seed when it smashes
into the ground?</p> </li>

</ol></p>

