<exercises xml:id="quick-practice-des" class="unnumbered">
<title>Quick practice</title>

<exercise><statement> <p> Is <m>\dfrac{dq}{dt} = 2.1q(1-q)</m> a
pure-time or
autonomous differential equation?</p> </statement>
<solution>
<p> In <m>\dfrac{dq}{dt} = 2.1q(1-q)</m>, the unknown
quantity that is being differentiated, <m>q = q(t)</m>, appears on the
right-hand side, and does so in the absence of the variable <m>t</m> on
the right-hand side, this is indicative of an autonomous equation.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><statement>  <p> Compute <m>\displaystyle\int
3x+2\,dx</m>.</p> </statement>
<solution>
<p> The indefinite integral <m>\displaystyle\int
3x+2\,dx</m> evaluates to <m>\displaystyle\int 3x+2\,dx =
\dfrac{3}{2}x^{2}+2x+c</m>.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>


<exercise><statement>  <p> What quantity is obtained when a pure-time
growth rate
indicating a rate of change of length is integrated?</p> </statement>
<solution>
<p> Integrating the rate of change of length gives length
itself as a function of time.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><statement>  <p> Compute <m>\displaystyle\int 0\,dx</m>.</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p> The indefinite integral <m>\displaystyle\int 0\,dx</m>
evaluates to <m>\displaystyle\int 0\,dx = c</m>.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>
</exercises>
